tr.td: She has classic clinical signs and symptoms of carpal tunnel syndrome. There are positive provocative signs present. Electrodiagnostic testing performed some years ago was consistent with carpal tunnel syndrome. I discussed the options with her. She wishes to proceed with left carpal tunnel release. The risks and benefits were discussed and her questions answered.

Susan is a very pleasant 66-year-old here for evaluation of 2-month history of left leg pain. Goes from the buttock down to the calf is gotten worse. Initially just in the buttock down the in the thigh. It is worse with coughing, sneezing and bowel movement is aggravated by flexion extension of the spine. She reports no numbness and tingling the pain is always very low level 2-4 and up to get accelerates up to 8-9. She reports no bowel bladder function no weakness no gait disturbance no numbness or tingling.
Review of systems remarkable for hypertension depression hyperlipidemia.
Review of system pression physical examination alert oriented female slender not in apparent distress normal behavior, affect, posture, normal gait and stance extension flexion of the spine aggravate the pain in her leg. Straight leg raise causes pain in the leg. She is neurologic intact motor, sensory deep tendon testing both lower extremities. Right leg is unremarkable contralateral straight leg raise is negative. She has normal motion hips, knees, ankles, feet and toes. I can elicit the pain by femoral nerve stretch when I do not hold her pelvis level but on and she mild pelvis level is minimal. Pulses are symmetrical. Skin is warm dry. X-rays lumbar spine 2 views ordered, taken interpreted and demonstrate mild degenerative change L4-5 L5-S1
Pression lumbar radiculopathy
Plan Medrol Dosepak, home exercises physician directed see her back in 4 to 6 weeks if she not improved in 3 to 4 weeks we will consider MRI

Ms. Williams is back for review of her MRI the MRI is reviewed spoke to the radiologist impression very osteoporotic he has a large synovial cyst L4-5 left and this is causing her radiculopathy incidentally she has a mass on the inferior pole the right kidney which has calcifications and possibly something in the realm of neoplastic process. With that in mind I have urged her to see her primary care doctor we will bring her disc to give her the report today she is to be evaluate for that with the lumbar radiculopathy from the cyst we will order transforaminal epidural steroids L4-5 hopefully rupturing the cyst. Spent better than 50% of the 20-minute visit today discussing this and necessity for evaluation of this mass on the kidney.
Pression lumbar tracheotomy secondary synovial cyst 4 5 left return as needed

PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:
1. Right carpal tunnel syndrome.
POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:
1. Right carpal tunnel syndrome.
OPERATIONS PERFORMED:
1. Right carpal tunnel release.
SURGEON: Christopher J. Walsh, M.D.
ANESTHESIA: MAC with Local.
BLOOD LOSS: Minimal.
COMPLICATIONS: None.
DISPOSITION: PACU.
OPERATIVE INDICATIONS: Right hand numbness and pain.
DESCRIPTION OF PROCEDURE: The patient was brought to the operating room and placed in the supine position. Intravenous sedation was administered. Following a surgical pause, under sterile conditions I injected 10ml 1% lidocaine with epinephrine into the skin and subcutaneous tissues starting proximal to the wrist crease and working distal through the carpal tunnel area. The right upper extremity was prepped sterilely and draped free. Loupe magnification was used for the procedure. Following a surgical pause and confirmation of adequate anesthesia, An Esmarch bandage was used to exsanguinate the limb and the tourniquet inflated to 250 mmHg. A longitudinal incision was made in the proximal portion of the palm in line with the radial border of the ring ray. Subcutaneous tissues were divided. Bipolar electrocautery was used to maintain hemostasis. The palmar fascia was incised longitudinally and a self-retaining retractor placed. The transverse carpal ligament was identified. It was divided sharply with the #15 blade in its mid and distal portions. I used tenotomy scissors distally extending to the fat pad in the palm. Proximally, I freed up the ligament from surrounding soft tissues, spreading above and below, and identifying the median nerve and synovium. The curved Mayo scissors were then used to divide the proximal portion of the transverse carpal ligament and the distal antebrachial fascia under direct vision. The canal was inspected. There were no space-occupying lesions. The incision was closed with interrupted moncryl sutures. Dry, sterile dressings were applied. The tourniquet was lowered. The patient tolerated the procedure well.

She is having increased numbness and tingling involving the right hand. Electrodiagnostic testing was consistent with right carpal tunnel syndrome.
